{"author":{"id":"30a9cdd9e5369167dc36be4d3e5f98e516aa30b7571a17013bc815eef45f09c3"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1445423820,"nonce":"s0ssO3QLXQaF/pDG7b0/oUKBkro=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0OTg1MDM4Nw==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/345#issuecomment-149850387"},"message":"\u003e I think the HTML comment suffix is a bit hacky. It requires to add these #https:// suffixes to each url within every galaxy wrapper but leaving them out can't break the system (these suffixes are never passed through to a server). Because it doesn't break when it's missing it probably get's used less frequently over time, unless planemo will be modified. I don't think html suffixes are designed for this purpose.\n\nThey're not, you're right, it is a bit hacky. It was the decision to have one moving part (i.e. dynamic script that has to be running 24/7) versus ZERO and I chose the latter. Agreed, there is the chance that people use the human readable URL fragment less. I don't have a solution for that under my current scheme.\n\n\u003e (I am not sure if I understand this correctly, but I suppose you mean that files are being accessed by their sha256sum?)\n\u003e \n\u003e If so, this implies that hash collisions will never take place ;)\n\nYep! Files are stored and accessed by their sha256. There's a reason we use that and not md5... sha256 ia a cryptogeaphically appropriate signature, the probability of a collision is really not a concern. http://stackoverflow.com/a/4014407\n\nThat said, I agree with your points. If anyone else feels similarly I'll add a script which will have to always be running, to map URLs to files on disk.","files":null}]}